Diagnosis.
Males: clypeus subrectangular, apex convex (
Fig. 2C
); ocular canthi anteriorly protruding, posteriorly acute (
Fig. 3C
); internal lobe of mandibles partially covered by mesal brush (
Fig. 5B
); mentum subtrapezoidal with apical corners carinate (
Fig. 5E
); parameres, in ventral view, with apex acute, ventral carina basally round, inferior edge of parameres deeply concave (
Fig. 6E
). Females: clypeus trapezoidal, punctures absent on middle of vertex (
Fig. 7C
); frons with two distinct tubercles (
Fig. 7D
); mentum subtrapezoidal, apical corners with a weak carina (
Fig. 8E
).
